Fukushima and the Collapse of Derivatives
CAMBRIDGE – Financial commentators have likened the earthquake, tsunami, and Japanese nuclear disaster to the role of derivatives in the 2008 financial crisis.
The resemblance is quite clear: each of these activities generates large profits and involves a very low but explosive risk.
Yet, the similarity between the two types of crises ends where the way to prevent their recurrence begins.
In the case of the Fukushima nuclear plant, a once-in-a-century flood, combined with otherwise harmless design flaws, caused the shutdown of cooling water circulation in the reactors and significant radiation leaks.
Regarding financial markets, an unexpected collapse of real estate values, combined with design flaws in derivative and repo markets, has damaged the ability of major financial institutions to honor their debts.
While basic risks originate outside systems – a tsunami for Fukushima, over-investment in mortgage loans for financial institutions – design defects and a lack of resilience ensured that the systems could not contain the damage.
In the United States, AIG, Bear Stearns, and Lehman Brothers – all with significant investments in derivatives and/or repos – went bankrupt, causing a freeze in credit on the markets for several long weeks.
We now understand quite well the risks and design flaws of Fukushima.
It cannot be said the same about the risks of derivatives that shook the global economy.
In Fukushima, teams of workers valiantly try to stop the radiation leaks.
On the other hand, for derivatives products, similar efforts are misdirected and will not allow us to avoid the next financial crisis.
We are recreating derivative products and similar financial structures over the same errors that remain active.
Financial actors use financial instruments to transfer risk: for example, one actor accepts the risk of euro fluctuations but does not want the risk on the yen, while for another, it will be the opposite.
In this case, the first promises to supply euros on June 1st, and the second promises to supply yens.
If a currency loses value compared to another, the loser pays the difference.
Repos are financial transactions.
Financial firms sell assets such as Treasury bonds or mortgage debts for cash and promise to repurchase these assets later, typically the next day (hence the name "repo," which is an abbreviation for the English verb repurchase – or repurchase, ndt).
The problem is that the cash coming from these short-term repos represents a significant portion of the balance sheets of the most important financial institutions, which means that simple financial tremors can have a major impact on them.
Some institutions may then find themselves without access to repo financing, as happened in 2008, and go bankrupt, like Bear Stearns.
Individually, derivatives or repo transactions are not much to blame.
Each one separately shifts risk in a legitimate manner to those who are better able to bear it, or allows for financial participation.
However, when used excessively by institutions that are systemically vital, they can blow up the financial system due to its design flaws.
To this day, about 70% of the liabilities of major American financial companies consist of very short-term loans, such as repos payable the next day.
In the United States, the main design defects lie in the bankruptcy legislation, which exempts derivatives and repos from most usual constraints in case of bankruptcy.
For example, investors who hold derivative contracts orrepos with financially fragile institutions may seize the company's assets before – and at the expense of – its normal creditors. In doing so, they may decide its fate when, with just a bit more time, the company could have survived.
Such actions ruined AIG, Bear Stearns, and others during the financial crisis.
Worse still, because investors in derivatives and repos end up at the front of the repayment queue in so many ways, they have fewer incentives to encourage market discipline by closely checking their counterparties' solvency and carefully rationing their exposure to any single counterparty.
Typically, they will be repaid, anyway.
After all, someone has to be first.
Other financial actors must shoulder more risk because exemptions for derivative actors and repo place them at the forefront in case of bankruptcy.
Normally, one would expect that these others would therefore have an interest in encouraging more market discipline.
But the next actor in line is often the American government, acting as the guarantor of "too-big-to-fail" financial institutions (too important to fail, ndt). However, the government is poorly positioned to regulate these markets on a daily basis.
It is not financially agile; it is often confined to the regulated market; and, when economic conditions are good, no official would want to spoil the party.
The American Congress had an opportunity to address this flaw in the major overhaul of finance it adopted last summer through the Dodd-Frank legislation.
But he did not grasp it.
If investors in derivatives, pensions, and credit-default swaps (credit-event derivatives, ndt) were not granted favorable treatment, they would behave differently.
First and foremost, they would insist more often that their counterparties be adequately capitalized.
They accepted the risk associated with ultra-low capitalization when it was essentially the money of the American government; they would be less inclined to do so if it were their own money at stake.
The public perceives the risks of Fukushima and the risks associated with derivatives differently.
Many people fear nuclear risks, which are stark and cause a slowdown in an industry that must address safety concerns.
However, the risks associated with derivatives and repos are poorly understood, difficult to communicate in the media, and complicated for politicians to debate and resolve.
During a crisis, these markets attract public attention and derision, but when the economy stabilizes again, ordinary people lose interest, leaving the financial sector to control its own destiny with the legislative body.
Regarding the Fukushima-type risks, analysts are already discussing how nuclear power plants can be designed and built to contain earthquake and tsunami-related risks through passive cooling systems.
Today, it is considered possible to predict nuclear power plants that can maintain cold fuel rods even in the absence of total electrical power supply.
Contrairement à cela, only modest progress has been made so far to prevent the damages that the priority of derivative products and their repose in case of bankruptcy could cause during a new financial system crisis.
New rules are being developed, which require that final users (like oil companies using derivatives to protect themselves against unexpected changes in oil prices) and others post high-quality collateral.
However, these rules do not address the main issue: the weak market discipline incentives for the major financial institutions.
It's as if we were reacting to Fukushima by better controlling gas emissions in oil extraction projects.
We should examine how to make investors in derivatives fully bear the risk associated with their decisions when they engage with financial institutions that are systemically critical.
Au lieu de cela, nous avons survécu au tsunami financier de 2008 seulement pour reconstruire au même endroit, avec les mêmes défauts financiers et selon le même design défectueux.
